      "section_title": "1.9 Rational Expressions and Equations",
      
      "introduction": "Rational expressions are fractions that contain variables. They appear in many real-world contexts - rates (speed = distance/time), work problems (how long to complete a task together), and proportions (scale models, unit conversions). Mastering rational expressions builds on your knowledge of fractions and polynomial operations, and is essential for success in advanced mathematics.",
      
      "introduction_image": {
        "src": "images/unit1/section1.9/rational_intro_graphic.png",
        "alt": "Rational expressions introduction",
        "caption": "Figure 1.9.2: Rational expressions model rates, proportions, and many real situations."
      },
      
      "key_concept": {
        "definition": "A **rational expression** is an expression of the form $\\frac{P}{Q}$ where $P$ and $Q$ are polynomials and $Q \\neq 0$.\n\n**Domain (Excluded Values)**: Since division by zero is undefined, any value that makes the denominator zero must be excluded from the domain. Find excluded values by setting each denominator factor equal to zero.\n\n**Simplifying Rational Expressions**:\n1. Factor numerator and denominator completely\n2. Identify common factors\n3. Cancel common factors\n4. Note any new restrictions from canceled factors? Actually, restrictions come from ORIGINAL denominator\n\n**Operations with Rational Expressions**:\n• **Multiplication**: Factor first, then multiply numerators and denominators, cancel common factors\n• **Division**: Multiply by the reciprocal of the divisor, then multiply as above\n• **Addition/Subtraction**: Find LCD, rewrite each fraction with LCD, combine numerators, simplify\n\n**Solving Rational Equations**:\n1. Find the LCD of all denominators\n2. Multiply both sides of equation by LCD\n3. Solve the resulting polynomial equation\n4. Check for extraneous solutions (solutions that make any denominator zero in original equation)",
        
        "context": "Rational expressions model countless real situations: average speed (distance/time), work rates (portion of job per hour), unit pricing (cost per ounce), and proportions in similar figures. In science, they appear in formulas like Ohm's law ($I = V/R$) and concentration calculations.",
        
        "image": {
