  "summary": "Section 1.9 covers rational expressions and equations. Rational expressions are fractions with polynomials. Always identify excluded values (where denominators = 0) first. Simplify by factoring and canceling common factors. For multiplication and division, factor first, then multiply numerators/denominators and cancel. For addition and subtraction, find the LCD, rewrite each fraction, combine numerators, and simplify. Complex fractions can be simplified by combining numerator and denominator separately or multiplying by the common denominator. To solve rational equations, multiply both sides by the LCD to clear denominators, solve the resulting polynomial equation, and check for extraneous solutions (values that make any original denominator zero). Applications include work problems (rates adding), distance-rate-time problems, and proportions. Mastering rational expressions is essential for advanced algebra, calculus, and real-world problem-solving.",

